      Ackman SPAC attack
   =20
 =20
One basic way to invest is that you put your money in a pot, and a bunch of=
 other people put their money in the pot, and one person manages the pot of=
 money and uses it to invest in stuff. If the stuff she invests in goes up,=
 you, and the other people who put money into the pot, make money. (If it g=
oes down, you lose money.) If the stuff goes up, and usually also if it goe=
s down, the manager gets paid somehow =E2=80=94=C2=A0fees, salaries, bonuse=
s, a share of the profits, a share of the pot, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0for doin=
g the work of picking the investments.This general description covers a lot=
 of things. In a sense it covers every public company. Loosely speaking Tes=
la Inc. raised a pot of money from investors, and Elon Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
its manager =E2=80=94=C2=A0invested that pot of money in factories and stuf=
f to make cars, and the value of those investments went up, and so Tesla=E2=
=80=99s shareholders made money and Musk was compensated in various ways (m=
ostly shares and options) that made him very rich.=C2=A0But most classicall=
y that description covers=C2=A0mutual funds. A mutual fund is a pot of mone=
y, its manager uses the money to buy stocks or bonds, if the stocks or bond=
s go up the shareholders of the fund make money, and the manager charges so=
me fees.=C2=A0Back in the 1920s, a bunch of nefarious things happened in th=
e stock market, including with mutual funds. Then the Great Depression happ=
ened and the=C2=A0U.S. Congress wrote what we now call the securities laws,=
 setting up a system of regulation of stock markets. One of these laws is t=
he Investment Company Act of 1940, generally called =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=994=
0 Act,=E2=80=9D which regulates mutual funds. Essentially the =E2=80=9940 A=
ct defines an =E2=80=9Cinvestment company=E2=80=9D (roughly synonymous with=
 =E2=80=9Cmutual fund=E2=80=9D) as a company that is mainly in the business=
 of investing in securities, requires investment companies to make lots of =
disclosures, and carefully regulates the relationships and conflicts of int=
erest between the investment company =E2=80=94=C2=A0the pot of money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and the people who manage it. In particular an investment company =
will have an =E2=80=9Cinvestment adviser,=E2=80=9D a person or more often a=
 company that manages the mutual fund, and the =E2=80=9940 Act (and the rel=
ated Investment Advisers Act of 1940)=C2=A0sets requirements for the invest=
ment company=E2=80=99s deal with the investment adviser. The investment adv=
iser can=E2=80=99t, for instance, trade securities with the investment comp=
any: If the adviser owns stocks, she can=E2=80=99t sell them to the mutual =
fund (to avoid the risk that she=E2=80=99d sell them at too high a price). =
The adviser=E2=80=99s fees are also regulated; in particular, it is hard fo=
r advisers to charge performance-based fees (i.e. take a cut of the fund=E2=
=80=99s upside).[1] There is a general sense that the requirements of the =
=E2=80=9940 Act are quite strict, that it severely limits the things that t=
he investment manager can do and the compensation she can receive.These rul=
es do not apply to, for instance, Tesla. Or WeWork. The chief executive off=
icer of a public company can have all sorts of compensation arrangements an=
d conflicts of interest that the investment adviser of a mutual fund could =
not. Those are general questions of corporate governance, and corporate gov=
ernance rules=C2=A0in general=C2=A0are less strict than the rules of the =
=E2=80=9940 Act. The =E2=80=9940 Act applies only to investment companies.=
=C2=A0Companies that are in the business of investing in car factories or w=
hatever are just regular companies and not covered. The key distinction is =
that a company that is mainly in the business of buying=C2=A0securities=C2=
=A0is an investment company, while a company that is mainly in the business=
 of buying other things =E2=80=94=C2=A0factories or real estate or whatever=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not.[2]Occasionally there are weird accidents. A company=
 will run an operating business and then come into possession of a ton of p=
ublicly traded securities. Perhaps it sold a division for stock, etc. Is it=
 an investment company? I dunno, maybe; sometimes temporarily holding a bun=
ch of shares (before dividending them out to your shareholders, etc.) is fi=
ne. There are technical rules but at our level of generality the point is t=
hat there are some companies that are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D in the busin=
ess of doing business, and those aren=E2=80=99t investment companies, and t=
here are other companies that are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D in the business =
of buying securities, and those are investment companies and subject to the=
 =E2=80=9940 Act.(There are other forms of =E2=80=9Cpeople put money in a p=
ot and a manager buys things with it=E2=80=9D that are not covered by=C2=A0=
the =E2=80=9940 Act for whatever reason. Hedge funds, for instance, are a s=
ort of investment firm that are limited to rich people and institutions, an=
d are exempt from=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act.[3] This gives hedge fund manage=
rs more flexibility to charge performance fees, to use leverage and short s=
elling, etc.)Another thing of the form =E2=80=9Cpeople put money in a pot a=
nd a manager buys things with it=E2=80=9D is the special-purpose acquisitio=
n company, or SPAC. In a SPAC, people put money into a pot, and the money s=
tays in the pot until the manager finds a company to merge with. Then the p=
ot merges with the target company; the target company gets the money and be=
comes public, while the shareholders of the pot get shares of the newly pub=
lic target. And the SPAC=E2=80=99s sponsor =E2=80=94=C2=A0the person who ra=
ised the money in the pot and found the target =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets a big ch=
unk of shares and warrants in the target company as compensation for her ef=
forts.In a generic sense, SPAC sponsors are a lot like mutual-fund investme=
nt advisers, but they get paid a lot more. They get a lot more performance =
fees. Their fees are less clear and more discretionary. They can engage in =
all sorts of conflicted transactions. (Here=E2=80=99s a  fun story about a =
guy who ran a=C2=A0SPAC and merged it with=C2=A0his daughter=E2=80=99s comp=
any.) A lot of people do not like SPACs. They feel bubbly. Their disclosure=
 is sometimes=C2=A0 not the best. There is a sense that SPACs have often be=
en a confusing and overhyped way for well-connected financiers to raise a l=
ot of money from ordinary people, take a lot of that money for themselves, =
and leave their investors=C2=A0with poor results.If you don=E2=80=99t like =
SPACs, a thought you might have is: Look, the =E2=80=9940 Act is designed s=
pecifically to address this sort of problem. There are people raising money=
 from the general public to make investments. Those people are being a bit =
aggressive in their fund-raising, and being=C2=A0very=C2=A0aggressive, and =
somewhat confusing, in their compensation structures.=C2=A0There are confli=
cts of interest and disclosure failings and asymmetric performance fees. Th=
ese are =E2=80=9940 Act problems that=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act is meant to =
solve. Except that SPACs are not=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act investment companies.=
Or are they? When I say that, in a SPAC, =E2=80=9Cpeople put money into a p=
ot, and the money stays in the pot until the manager finds a company to mer=
ge with,=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t mean that literally. There=E2=80=99s not =
a physical pot with some $100 bills in it. Until it finds a merger target, =
the SPAC holds its money in a trust account and generally invests it in ver=
y safe assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0typically short-term U.S. Treasury securities =
or Treasury money market funds. Technically those are securities.[4] From t=
he time it raises its money, until the time it does its merger, a SPAC is i=
nvesting basically 100% of its shareholders=E2=80=99 money in securities.Do=
es that make it an investment company? Probably not, no: It is not primaril=
y in the business of investing in securities; rather, it is primarily in th=
e business of finding an operating company to merge with, and it holds secu=
rities for a while as it pursues that goal. But you could try. Here=E2=80=
