 =20
If your model of the Ackman SPAC lawsuit is =E2=80=9Cthey want to make SPAC=
s illegal by calling them investment companies,=E2=80=9D then the weird thi=
ng is that Ackman has solved that problem. Let=E2=80=99s say that tomorrow =
a court declares SPACs illegal. The illegal thing, this hypothetical court =
says, is that a SPAC:=09takes investors=E2=80=99 money;=C2=A0=09invests it =
in Treasury bills for a bit while it looks for an acquisition target, makin=
g it a =E2=80=9940 Act investment company; and=09charges lots of weird cool=
 fees, which are illegal under the =E2=80=9940 Act.Fine. Let=E2=80=99s say =
you are a SPAC sponsor who wants to keep doing this racket because it is lu=
crative. One thing you could (perhaps) do is keep doing SPACs but abiding b=
y the =E2=80=9940 Act rules about fees and=C2=A0related-party transactions;=
 I=E2=80=99m not sure this is even possible, but certainly it is unattracti=
ve to sponsors.=C2=A0Instead the move is to=C2=A0not be an investment compa=
ny, which means (in this hypothetical world where the Ackman SPAC lawsuit s=
ucceeds)=C2=A0not taking investors=E2=80=99 money and investing it in Treas=
uries. Just=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0take their money=C2=A0until you have an=
 acquisition target. Sign up investors on a sort of waitlist, go out and lo=
ok for an acquisition target, sign the merger agreement, and then go out to=
 the investors on the waitlist and say =E2=80=9Cokay you can put your money=
 in now.=E2=80=9DThis is the SPARC, the Special Purpose Acquisition Rights =
Company.=C2=A0A SPARC is a SPAC without the pool of money. Instead of share=
s, SPARCs issue rights; instead of selling shares for $10 or $20 per share =
and keeping the money in trust, the SPARC gives rights away for free and ha=
s no money in trust. It goes out and looks for a deal. When it finds one, i=
t goes to the holders of rights and says =E2=80=9Chey would you like to kic=
k in $10 to get a new public share of this company I found?=E2=80=9D If the=
y mostly say yes, then the deal closes, the acquisition target gets the mon=
ey and becomes public, and the SPARC rights (plus $10) transform into share=
s of the new public company.=C2=A0When Pershing Square Tontine Holdings ann=
ounced its Universal Music deal, it announced that PSTH shareholders, in ad=
dition to Universal Music shares, would be getting SPARC rights, and we tal=
ked about the SPARC structure a  couple of  times. It is cool! I am uncompl=
icatedly fond of the SPARC; it is an evolution of the SPAC structure that i=
s both (1) more efficient and investor-friendly (investors don=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to tie up cash for months while the sponsor hunts for a target) and (2) =
somehow funnier.  I wrote:It is fun. It dispenses with almost all of the fi=
nancial engineering of a SPAC: There are no warrants, no cash value, no sha=
reholder votes, no time limits. In fact arguably there is no anything. Bill=
 Ackman can go around to private companies looking to go public and say =E2=
=80=A6 what? =E2=80=9CHey, I=E2=80=99ve got some friends, and they are foll=
owing with interest my efforts to find a company to merge with. If I find a=
 good one, maybe they=E2=80=99ll give me money, though they haven=E2=80=99t=
 given me any money yet and they=E2=80=99re under no obligation to do so. W=
ould you like to be that company, and maybe my friends will give you their =
money? We can find out together!=E2=80=9DBut, I emphasized, the same exact =
thing is true of a SPAC: SPAC shareholders put their money in up front, but=
 they can get it back when the deal is announced; the target only gets the =
money if the SPAC shareholders decide it=E2=80=99s a good deal. The SPARC e=
mphasizes this choice: It emphasizes that, if you are a target company and =
you sign a deal with a SPA(R)C to go public, the SPA(R)C doesn=E2=80=99t co=
me with any guaranteed money. Instead, you are signing up for the sponsor=
=E2=80=99s ability to=C2=A0raise=C2=A0money, to go out to the retail invest=
ors holding SPAC shares or SPARC rights and convince them to fund the deal.=
Anyway, the Universal Music deal fell through, so PSTH did not end up doing=
 the SPARCs. But there=E2=80=99s still time. Here's a letter that Ackman se=
nt to PSTH shareholders last week, explaining and criticizing the =E2=80=99=
40 Act lawsuit against PSTH=C2=A0and telling them that a SPARC is coming[6]=
:We are working to accelerate the launch of Pershing Square SPARC Holdings,=
 Ltd. (=E2=80=9CSPARC=E2=80=9D), and expect that we will shortly be making =
a public filing of SPARC=E2=80=99s SEC registration statement. As a reminde=
r, SPARC, which we conceived of months ago and disclosed in connection with=
 the UMG transaction, is a modified opt-in (rather than the current opt-out=
) SPAC structure where investors in PSTH would receive long-dated, transfer=
able SPARC warrants to acquire common stock in SPARC, which we expect to be=
 traded on the NYSE.SPARC warrants would give investors the right to invest=
 in SPARC=E2=80=99s future merger transaction at a share price equal to SPA=
RC=E2=80=99s cash net asset value (=E2=80=9CNAV=E2=80=9D) per share. The Pe=
rshing Square Funds will be making a large-co-investment in SPARC on precis=
ely the same terms and at the same time as SPARC=C2=A0warrant holders. The =
SPARC warrants would not be exercisable, and warrant holders would not need=
 to invest their capital, until SPARC has identified a merger target, compl=
eted due diligence, entered into and approved a transaction, and cleared a =
registration statement with the SEC, which will provide full disclosure on =
the transaction and the target company.Originally, SPARC intended to issue =
the SPARC warrants to PSTH shareholders after PSTH=E2=80=99s initial busine=
ss combination. In light of this litigation, we expect that SPARC would iss=
ue the SPARC warrants as promptly as possible after regulatory approvals ar=
e obtained. =E2=80=A6Assuming SPARC is approved by the SEC and the SPARC wa=
rrants are approved for listing on the NYSE, if PSTH has not by then entere=
d into a merger transaction, we intend to seek PSTH shareholder approval to=
 enable us to return to shareholders the $4 billion of cash PSTH holds in t=
rust. Following the return of cash, we expect SPARC to issue one SPARC Dist=
ributable Warrant for each PSTH Distributable Warrant, and one SPARC warran=
t for each outstanding PSTH common share.=C2=A0As a result of the above, PS=
TH shareholders will receive $20 per share in cash and one SPARC warrant fo=
r each share that they own. This will entitle shareholders to invest in our=
 next initial business combination at a share price equal to SPARC=E2=80=99=
s cash NAV per share, or to sell the SPARC warrants on the NYSE.=C2=A0So if=
 all goes according to plan, PSTH will hand back all of its money to invest=
ors and disappear, and those investors will also get a SPARC right. And the=
n if Ackman finds a new merger target, those investors will be able to exer=
cise their SPARC rights to put in more money to fund the new deal. The SPAR=
C structure is cool and elegant, but the process to get there is pretty ugl=
y: Ackman (1) raised $4 billion, (2) now wants to hand it back, and (3) hop=
es to be able to raise it again in the future. Oh well.I want to make two m=
ore points about the SPARC structure. One is that, because it has no money,=
 it really puts an emphasis on the sponsor=E2=80=99s ability to do a good d=
eal, sell that deal, and raise money. In the SPAC boom of earlier this year=
, lots of random people raised SPACs because SPACs were hot. When those peo=
ple go to a target company and say =E2=80=9Chey we have a pot of money here=
, would you like it,=E2=80=9D the target will be tempted to say yes. This i=
s true even though the SPAC doesn=E2=80=99t really have a pot of money; the=
 SPAC shareholders can take their money out before the deal closes.=C2=A0Wi=
th a SPARC, on the other hand, the sponsor can=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Chey w=
e have a pool of money here=E2=80=9D; all the sponsor can say is =E2=80=9Ch=
ey there are some people who have an option to give me money if I strike a =
good deal.=E2=80=9D If you are a target company, you=E2=80=99re only going =
to do a deal with a sponsor who you think can deliver.The other point is we=
irder: How do you=C2=A0start=C2=A0a SPARC? The way to start a SPAC is clear=
: You sell shares for $10, you put all the $10 checks=C2=A0in a pot, you go=
 look for deals. The shares are sold in a public offering, and investment b=
anks are used to doing those offerings. Investors who buy in the offering p=
ay $10, and can get $10 back at the end if you don=E2=80=99t do a deal (or =
if they don=E2=80=99t like the deal that you do), so the offering feels pre=
tty safe.With a SPARC, though, you can=E2=80=99t really do an initial publi=
c offering of SPARC rights. Those rights are in some loose sense worth zero=
 dollars. Of course they aren=E2=80=99t: You=E2=80=99ll list them on the st=
ock exchange and they=E2=80=99ll trade for some price, and that price will =
reflect people=E2=80=99s expectations that (1) you=E2=80=99ll sign a deal w=
ith a target company, (2) they will like the deal and exercise the rights, =
and (3) the price you agree to pay per share of the target company will be =
lower than the trading value of those shares, so they will get a pop by exe=
rcising their rights. If you are a decent SPARC sponsor that price will be =
greater than zero. But those things are pretty uncertain, and if you sold t=
he rights for, like, $2 a share and then didn=E2=80=99t do a deal =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0letting the rights expire worthless =E2=80=94=C2=A0investors and regu=
lators would be pretty mad at you. I think the only realistic price that a =
SPARC=C2=A0sponsor=C2=A0could charge for SPARC rights is $0, even though th=
ey would then trade up to a non-zero price.[7]=C2=A0So how do you give SPAR=
C rights away for free? Well, Ackman has a simple solution: He has a SPAC, =
and he=E2=80=99s going to give SPARC rights to his SPAC shareholders. One S=
PAC share gets you one SPARC right. Fine. He was planning to do that after =
the SPAC closed its Universal Music deal, and now that that deal is dead he=
=E2=80=99s planning to do it when the SPAC hands its cash back to sharehold=
ers. Any=C2=A0other=C2=A0SPAC sponsor could also do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0sta=
rt a SPARC, hand SPARC rights out to your SPAC shareholders, either do a de=
al with your SPAC or shut it down, and keep the SPARC around to do your nex=
t deal. There are serial SPAC sponsors; they could easily become serial SPA=
RC sponsors instead. Each time you do a deal, give out new SPARC rights to =
the shareholders of that deal.But what if you don=E2=80=99t already have a =
SPAC? You=E2=80=99re some brilliant financier or operator who wants to get =
into the taking-companies-public business; you would start a SPAC, but you'=
re convinced that the SPARC structure is better. (More investor-friendly, l=
ess likely to get you in =E2=80=9940 Act trouble, etc.) The problem you hav=
e is giving a bunch of rights away for free, to some defined group of peopl=
e, preferably people who are likely to (1) exercise the rights if you find =
a deal or (2) at least sell the rights to someone who might exercise.I supp=
ose one thing you could do is call up Bill Ackman and say =E2=80=9Chey, you=
=E2=80=99ve got a SPAC,[8] I would like to give your SPAC shareholders a pr=
esent, could you send me your shareholder list?=E2=80=9D And then you distr=
ibute your SPARC rights to every shareholder of PSTH. Or you call up some o=
ther SPAC sponsor, get their shareholder list, and distribute SPARC rights =
to their shareholders. Or you call up Warren Buffett and distribute your SP=
ARC rights to Berkshire Hathaway Inc. shareholders. Or you print out SPARC =
right certificates on paper and go door to door in Greenwich, Connecticut, =
depositing one in each resident=E2=80=99s mailbox. Or you put them on the E=
thereum blockchain and distribute one to each holder of Ether. The way to s=
tart a SPARC is, as crypto people would say, with  an =E2=80=9Cairdrop=E2=
=80=9D: Find some big but definable group of possibly interested people and=
 give them SPARC rights for free.
