 can charge =E2=80=9Cfulcrum fees.=E2=80=9D (Meaning they take a cut of the=
 downside too.) But it=E2=80=99s rare. (Because of the downside.) Also stri=
ctly speaking the rules about fees are in the Investment Advisers Act of 19=
40, which is, uh, a different =E2=80=9940 Act.[2] See section 3(a)(1)=C2=A0=
of the =E2=80=9940 Act, which defines an =E2=80=9Cinvestment company=E2=80=
=9D to include a company that =E2=80=9Cis or holds itself out as being enga=
ged primarily, or proposes to engage primarily, in the business of investin=
g, reinvesting, or trading in securities,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cis engaged o=
r proposes to engage in the business of investing, reinvesting, owning, hol=
ding, or trading in securities, and owns or proposes to acquire investment =
securities having a value exceeding 40 per centum of the value of such issu=
er=E2=80=99s total assets (exclusive of Government securities and cash item=
s).=E2=80=9D=C2=A0[3] A company =E2=80=9Cthe outstanding securities of whic=
h are owned exclusively by persons who, at the time of acquisition of such =
securities, are qualified purchasers, and which is not making and does not =
at that time propose to make a public offering of such securities,=E2=80=9D=
 is exempt from the =E2=80=9940 Act (see section 3(c)(7)). =E2=80=9CQualifi=
ed purchaser=E2=80=9D means what you=E2=80=99d expect (rich person, institu=
tion, etc.). So a mutual fund offered to the public is covered by the =E2=
=80=9940 Act, but a hedge fund offered only to rich or institutional invest=
ors is not.[4] Section 3(a)(2) of=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act defines a thing =
called =E2=80=9Cinvestment securities,=E2=80=9D which *excludes* Treasury s=
ecurities. Section 3(a)(1)(C) says that a company is an investment company =
if more than 40% of its assets are investment securities; SPACs are not inv=
estment companies under that test. But section 3(a)(1)(A) says that a compa=
ny is an investment company if it =E2=80=9Cis or holds itself out as being =
engaged primarily, or proposes to engage primarily, in the business of inve=
sting, reinvesting, or trading in securities=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0securi=
ties, not =E2=80=9Cinvestment securities.=E2=80=9D So if you launch a Treas=
ury-bond fund whose only business is buying and trading Treasuries, that=E2=
=80=99s an investment company, even though you never buy =E2=80=9Cinvestmen=
t securities.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0[5] As Ackman points out in his letter to PSTH =
shareholders, one person at the SEC who never noticed this was Robert Jacks=
on. From the letter: =E2=80=9CNotably, one of the professors who is leading=
 the suit, Robert Jackson, served as an SEC Commissioner between January 20=
18 and February 2020. During his more than two-year term as Commissioner, t=
he SEC reviewed and declared effective more than 100 SPAC IPO registration =
statements, and oversaw dozens of de-SPAC merger transactions. If Mr. Jacks=
on is so sure that SPACs are in fact illegal investment companies, why didn=
=E2=80=99t he take steps to shut them down while he was an SEC Commissioner=
?=E2=80=9D[6] He says =E2=80=9Cwarrants=E2=80=9D where I might prefer to sa=
y =E2=80=9Crights.=E2=80=9D The point is, you get an option that entitles y=
ou to put in money and get back a share of stock in the new company.[7] Thi=
nk of it this way: A typical SPAC sells shares for $10, and shareholders ge=
t (1) $10 in a pot plus (2) the option to invest that $10 in a deal. That o=
ption to invest, for a good SPAC sponsor in good times for SPACs, is worth =
more than $0, and during the early-2021=C2=A0SPAC boom many SPACs would qui=
ckly trade up to like $12 a share after going public. But the SPAC sponsor =
wouldn=E2=80=99t sell the shares for $12, or whatever the market would bear=
; the sponsor would sell the shares for $10, the amount of cash that it wou=
ld keep in trust to hand back to shareholders if no deal happened. A SPARC =
is the same as a SPAC except that instead of $10 in trust it keeps $0 in tr=
ust. It=E2=80=99s a SPAC minus $10. As with a SPAC, the option to invest is=
 worth something; $12 minus $10 is $2. But as with a SPAC, you=E2=80=99re n=
ot going to charge for that option; you=E2=80=99re only going to charge inv=
estors the amount of money they=E2=80=99re guaranteed to get back =E2=80=94=
 here, $0.[8] Or, if all goes well, you call him in a few months and say =
=E2=80=9Chey, you=E2=80=99ve got a SPARC.=E2=80=9D Same basic principle.[9]=
 Again, though, the other possibility is that my readers are smart but very=
 ethical; they=C2=A0love thinking of clever hypotheticals but would never e=
ver do this.=C2=A0
