<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ackman SPAC attack</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One basic way to invest is that you pu=
t your money in a pot, and a bunch of other people put their money in the p=
ot, and one person manages the pot of money and uses it to invest in stuff.=
 If the stuff she invests in goes up, you, and the other people who put mon=
ey into the pot, make money. (If it goes down, you lose money.) If the stuf=
f goes up, and usually also if it goes down, the manager gets paid somehow =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0fees, salaries, bonuses, a share of the profits, a share of =
the pot, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0for doing the work of picking the investments.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This general description covers a lot of t=
hings. In a sense it covers every public company. Loosely speaking Tesla In=
c. raised a pot of money from investors, and Elon Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0its m=
anager =E2=80=94=C2=A0invested that pot of money in factories and stuff to =
make cars, and the value of those investments went up, and so Tesla=E2=80=
=99s shareholders made money and Musk was compensated in various ways (most=
ly shares and options) that made him very rich.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">But most classically that description covers=C2=A0<em>mutual fun=
ds</em>. A mutual fund is a pot of money, its manager uses the money to buy=
 stocks or bonds, if the stocks or bonds go up the shareholders of the fund=
 make money, and the manager charges some fees.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Back in the 1920s, a bunch of nefarious things happened in the s=
tock market, including with mutual funds. Then the Great Depression happene=
d and the=C2=A0U.S. Congress wrote what we now call the securities laws, se=
tting up a system of regulation of stock markets. One of these laws is <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuZ292aW5mby5nb3YvY29udGVudC9wa2cvQ09NUFMtMTg3OS9wZGYvQ09NUFMtMTg3O=
S5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd74b8300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Investment Company Act of 1940</a>, ge=
nerally called =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=9940 Act,=E2=80=9D which regulates mutua=
l funds. Essentially the =E2=80=9940 Act defines an =E2=80=9Cinvestment com=
pany=E2=80=9D (roughly synonymous with =E2=80=9Cmutual fund=E2=80=9D) as a =
company that is mainly in the business of investing in securities, requires=
 investment companies to make lots of disclosures, and carefully regulates =
the relationships and conflicts of interest between the investment company =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the pot of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the people who manage it=
. In particular an investment company will have an =E2=80=9Cinvestment advi=
ser,=E2=80=9D a person or more often a company that manages the mutual fund=
, and the =E2=80=9940 Act (and the related Investment Advisers Act of 1940)=
=C2=A0sets requirements for the investment company=E2=80=99s deal with the =
investment adviser. The investment adviser can=E2=80=99t, for instance, tra=
de securities with the investment company: If the adviser owns stocks, she =
can=E2=80=99t sell them to the mutual fund (to avoid the risk that she=E2=
=80=99d sell them at too high a price). The adviser=E2=80=99s fees are also=
 regulated; in particular, it is hard for advisers to charge performance-ba=
sed fees (i.e. take a cut of the fund=E2=80=99s upside).[1] There is a gene=
ral sense that the requirements of the =E2=80=9940 Act are quite strict, th=
at it severely limits the things that the investment manager can do and the=
 compensation she can receive.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These rules =
do not apply to, for instance, Tesla. Or WeWork. The chief executive office=
r of a public company can have all sorts of compensation arrangements and c=
onflicts of interest that the investment adviser of a mutual fund could not=
. Those are general questions of corporate governance, and corporate govern=
ance rules=C2=A0<em>in general=C2=A0</em>are less strict than the rules of =
the =E2=80=9940 Act. The =E2=80=9940 Act applies only to investment compani=
es.=C2=A0Companies that are in the business of investing in car factories o=
r whatever are just regular companies and not covered. The key distinction =
is that a company that is mainly in the business of buying=C2=A0<em>securit=
ies=C2=A0</em>is an investment company, while a company that is mainly in t=
he business of buying other things =E2=80=94=C2=A0factories or real estate =
or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Occas=
ionally there are weird accidents. A company will run an operating business=
 and then come into possession of a ton of publicly traded securities. Perh=
aps it sold a division for stock, etc. Is it an investment company? I dunno=
, maybe; sometimes temporarily holding a bunch of shares (before dividendin=
g them out to your shareholders, etc.) is fine. There are technical rules b=
ut at our level of generality the point is that there are some companies th=
at are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D in the business of doing business, and thos=
e aren=E2=80=99t investment companies, and there are other companies that a=
re =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D in the business of buying securities, and those=
 are investment companies and subject to the =E2=80=9940 Act.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(There are other forms of =E2=80=9Cpeople put money in=
 a pot and a manager buys things with it=E2=80=9D that are not covered by=
=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act for whatever reason. Hedge funds, for instance, a=
re a sort of investment firm that are limited to rich people and institutio=
ns, and are exempt from=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act.[3] This gives hedge fund =
managers more flexibility to charge performance fees, to use leverage and s=
hort selling, etc.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing of the fo=
rm =E2=80=9Cpeople put money in a pot and a manager buys things with it=E2=
=80=9D is the special-purpose acquisition company, or SPAC. In a SPAC, peop=
le put money into a pot, and the money stays in the pot until the manager f=
inds a company to merge with. Then the pot merges with the target company; =
the target company gets the money and becomes public, while the shareholder=
s of the pot get shares of the newly public target. And the SPAC=E2=80=99s =
sponsor =E2=80=94=C2=A0the person who raised the money in the pot and found=
 the target =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets a big chunk of shares and warrants in the t=
arget company as compensation for her efforts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">In a generic sense, SPAC sponsors are a lot like mutual-fund investment=
 advisers, but they get paid a lot more. They get a lot more performance fe=
es. Their fees are less clear and more discretionary. They can engage in al=
l sorts of conflicted transactions. (Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTgvc3BhYy1iYWNrZWQtYnktZmF0aGVyLW=
Z1ZWxzLTg0LWdhaW4tYnV5aW5nLWZpcm0tcnVuLWJ5LWRhdWdodGVy/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB13483592" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> fun story</a> about a guy who ran a=C2=A0SPAC and merged it with=C2=
=A0his daughter=E2=80=99s company.) A lot of people do not like SPACs. They=
 feel bubbly. Their disclosure is sometimes=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1=
pcG9z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35738e65" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not the best</a>. There is a sense that S=
PACs have often been a confusing and overhyped way for well-connected finan=
ciers to raise a lot of money from ordinary people, take a lot of that mone=
y for themselves, and leave their investors=C2=A0with <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1=
lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wOC8yMS9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9zcGFjLW1hcmtldC1mdXR1cmUuaH=
RtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e17dc27" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">poor results</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">If you don=E2=80=99t like SPACs, a thought you might have is: Look, th=
e =E2=80=9940 Act is designed specifically to address this sort of problem.=
 There are people raising money from the general public to make investments=
. Those people are being a bit aggressive in their fund-raising, and being=
=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>aggressive, and somewhat confusing, in their compe=
nsation structures.=C2=A0There are conflicts of interest and disclosure fai=
lings and asymmetric performance fees. These are =E2=80=9940 Act problems t=
hat=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act is meant to solve. Except that SPACs are not=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act investment companies.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Or are they? When I say that, in a SPAC, =E2=80=9Cpeople put money into a =
pot, and the money stays in the pot until the manager finds a company to me=
rge with,=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t mean that literally. There=E2=80=99s not=
 a physical pot with some $100 bills in it. Until it finds a merger target,=
 the SPAC holds its money in a trust account and generally invests it in ve=
ry safe assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0typically short-term U.S. Treasury securities=
 or Treasury money market funds. Technically those are securities.[4] From =
the time it raises its money, until the time it does its merger, a SPAC is =
investing basically 100% of its shareholders=E2=80=99 money in securities.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does that make it an investment company? Pr=
obably not, no: It is not primarily in the business of investing in securit=
ies; rather, it is primarily in the business of finding an operating compan=
y to merge with, and it holds securities for a while as it pursues that goa=
l. But you could try. Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMTcvcGVyc2hpbmctc3F1YXJlLXNwYWMtaGl0LXdpdGgtc3Vpd=
C1xdWVzdGlvbmluZy1pdHMtbGVnYWxpdHk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaaf87225" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg arti=
cle from last week</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lar=
gest SPAC to ever hit the market is operating illegally as an investment co=
mpany, a new lawsuit against billionaire Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s Pershing Squ=
are Tontine Holdings Ltd. claims.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Les=
s than a month after the blank-check company abandoned plans for a deal wit=
h Universal Music Group, it=E2=80=99s facing a civil suit from a shareholde=
r claiming that it fits the description of an investment company and should=
 be regulated as one, starting with the =E2=80=9Cstaggering=E2=80=9D compen=
sation paid to Pershing Square Capital Management as investment adviser.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The suit by shareholder George Assad could ha=
ve wide-ranging implications for the financial industry if a court determin=
es that SPACs more generally should be regarded as investment companies sub=
ject to the 1940 Investment Company Act, which requires registration with t=
