perhaps) do is keep doing SPACs but abiding by the =E2=80=9940 Act rules ab=
out fees and=C2=A0related-party transactions; I=E2=80=99m not sure this is =
even possible, but certainly it is unattractive to sponsors.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead the move is to=C2=A0<em>not be an investmen=
t company</em>, which means (in this hypothetical world where the Ackman SP=
AC lawsuit succeeds)=C2=A0<em>not taking investors=E2=80=99 money and inves=
ting it in Treasuries</em>. Just=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>take thei=
r money=C2=A0<em>until you have an acquisition target</em>. Sign up investo=
rs on a sort of waitlist, go out and look for an acquisition target, sign t=
he merger agreement, and then go out to the investors on the waitlist and s=
ay =E2=80=9Cokay you can put your money in now.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">This is the SPARC, the Special Purpose Acquisition Rights Com=
pany.=C2=A0A SPARC is a SPAC without the pool of money. Instead of shares, =
SPARCs issue rights; instead of selling shares for $10 or $20 per share and=
