</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I write a lot about insider trading, a=
nd my readers are smart, so the question I get asked perhaps more than any =
other goes like this:=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=
 =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s say I have some big secret news about a public comp=
any. Say I work for a company and know that it=E2=80=99s about to announce =
good earnings or be taken over at a premium. If I buy call options on my co=
mpany=E2=80=99s stock, that=E2=80=99s insider trading and I=E2=80=99ll go t=
o prison. But what if I buy call options on=C2=A0<em>another=C2=A0</em>comp=
any=E2=80=99s stock? What if I buy call options on my company=E2=80=99s clo=
sest competitor, figuring that good news for my company will also push up t=
hat company=E2=80=99s stock? I don=E2=80=99t have any inside information=C2=
=A0<em>about that company</em>, do I? So it=E2=80=99s not insider trading, =
right?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My answer has usually been =
what=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872=
.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDc=
tMTYvYS12YWNjaW5lLWNvdWxkLWN1cmUtYWlybGluZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7319d=
75b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I wro=
te last year</a>:</p><blockquote><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pad=
ding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This=
 is not legal advice.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The U.S. Sec=
urities and Exchange Commission will probably take the position that it=E2=
=80=99s illegal insider trading: You have=C2=A0nonpublic information, it is=
 (indirectly) material to Company Y, and you have some duty of confidential=
ity to Company X to keep it secret.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">But they are less likely to=C2=A0<em>catch=C2=A0</em>you than if yo=
u trade your own company=E2=80=99s stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Really, this is not legal advice!</li></ol></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">It is a curious fact that there is not a lot of precedent=
 for this. I mean, at the time I wrote that, I had never seen a court case =
or SEC enforcement action about this sort of comparable-company insider tra=
ding. You could interpret that in one of two ways:</p><ol style=3D"list-sty=
le-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Insider traders are uniformly dumb; when they have materia=
l nonpublic information they only use it to trade their own company=E2=80=
=99s stock, and get caught.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
Some insider traders are smart; when they have material nonpublic informati=
on they use it to trade the stock of highly correlated companies in order t=
o make quick reliable profits. But the SEC is dumb; it doesn=E2=80=99t have=
 tools to notice and go after this sort of trading: If you trade your own c=
ompany=E2=80=99s stock they=E2=80=99ll check up on you, but if you trade yo=
ur competitor=E2=80=99s stock they won=E2=80=99t.</li></ol><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Given how many times my readers have asked me about this hypot=
hetical, I have to assume that the answer is No. 2,=C2=A0that people regula=
rly use inside information about their own companies to make profitable tra=
des in the stock of other companies, and that the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t go af=
ter them.[9]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here=E2=80=99s an <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xNTU/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB83a4ddbb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">SEC enforcement action</a> from last week:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC's complaint, filed in the U.S. Distri=
ct Court for the Northern District of California, Matthew Panuwat, the then=
-head of business development at Medivation, a mid-sized, oncology-focused =
biopharmaceutical company, purchased short-term, out-of-the-money stock opt=
ions in Incyte Corporation, another mid-cap oncology-focused biopharmaceuti=
cal company, just days before the Aug. 22, 2016, announcement that Pfizer w=
ould acquire Medivation at a significant premium. Panuwat allegedly purchas=
ed the options within minutes of learning highly confidential information c=
oncerning the merger. According to the complaint, Panuwat knew that investm=
ent bankers had cited Incyte as a comparable company in discussions with Me=
divation and he anticipated that the acquisition of Medivation would likely=
 lead to an increase in Incyte's stock price. The complaint alleges that Me=
divation's insider trading policy expressly forbade Panuwat from using conf=
idential information he acquired at Medivation to trade in the securities o=
f any other publicly-traded company. Following the announcement of Medivati=
on's acquisition, Incyte's stock price increased by approximately 8%. The c=
omplaint alleges that, by trading ahead of the announcement, Panuwat genera=
ted illicit profits of $107,066.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">There you go! He learned about his company=E2=80=99s merger, bought call=
 options on his company=E2=80=99s closest comparable company, made money wh=
en the merger was announced and the other company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock went=
 up, and got charged with insider trading. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2V=
jLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0xNTUucGRm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e1a8dd5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s argument</a>=C2=A0that it=E2=80=99s i=
llegal insider trading.</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Panuwat=
 learned the foregoing information through his employment at Medivation, an=
d he knew or was reckless in not knowing that the information was material =
and nonpublic. Panuwat also knew, or was reckless in not knowing, that the =
information concerning Medivation=E2=80=99s imminent acquisition was materi=
al not only to Medivation, but also to Incyte, a peer company in the biopha=
rmaceutical industry that was also publicly-traded, mid-cap, and oncology-f=
ocused. Medivation=E2=80=99s undisclosed acquisition would have been viewed=
 by a reasonable investor in Medivation or Incyte as having significantly a=
ltered the total mix of information made available. The public announcement=
 of Medivation=E2=80=99s acquisition at a significant premium to its then-c=
urrent share price would likely have a positive impact on Incyte=E2=80=99s =
stock price. For example, the acquisition of Medivation also made Incyte a =
more attractive target for acquisition.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">By virtue of his employment at Medivation, as well as the confidentialit=
y and=C2=A0insider trading policies that he signed, Panuwat owed Medivation=
 a duty to keep this material nonpublic information confidential, and to re=
frain from trading on Medivation=E2=80=99s confidential<br />information.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems reasonable enough=
. They do not, however, say how they caught him. So now I need to update my=
 standard response:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left:=
 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is not le=
gal advice.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The U.S. Securities an=
d Exchange Commission will <em>definitely</em>=C2=A0take the position that =
it=E2=80=99s illegal insider trading: You have=C2=A0nonpublic information, =
it is (indirectly) material to Company Y, and you have some duty of confide=
ntiality to Company X to keep it secret.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Also this is apparently something they look for, so they might=
 catch you.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Really, this is not le=
gal advice!</li></ol><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" ce=
llspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
