b3YvY29udGVudC9wa2cvQ09NUFMtMTg3OS9wZGYvQ09NUFMtMTg3OS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cCd74b8300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">section 3(a)(1)</a>=C2=A0of the =E2=80=9940 Act, which defines an=
 =E2=80=9Cinvestment company=E2=80=9D to include a company that =E2=80=9Cis=
 or holds itself out as being engaged primarily, or proposes to engage prim=
arily, in the business of investing, reinvesting, or trading in securities,=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cis engaged or proposes to engage in the business of i=
nvesting, reinvesting, owning, holding, or trading in securities, and owns =
or proposes to acquire investment securities having a value exceeding 40 pe=
r centum of the value of such issuer=E2=80=99s total assets (exclusive of G=
overnment securities and cash items).=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;"><em><em>[3] A company =E2=80=9Cthe outstanding</em> securiti=
es of which are owned exclusively by persons who, at the time of acquisitio=
n of such securities, are qualified purchasers, and which is not making and=
 does not at that time propose to make a public offering of such securities=
,=E2=80=9D is exempt from the =E2=80=9940 Act (see <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ292aW5mby=
5nb3YvY29udGVudC9wa2cvQ09NUFMtMTg3OS9wZGYvQ09NUFMtMTg3OS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cDd74b8300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">section 3(c)(7)</a>). =E2=80=9CQualified purchaser=E2=80=9D me=
ans what you=E2=80=99d expect (rich person, institution, etc.). So a mutual=
 fund offered to the public is covered by the =E2=80=9940 Act, but a hedge =
fund offered only to rich or institutional investors is not.</em></p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[4] Section 3(a)(2) of=C2=A0the =E2=80=9940 Act =
defines a thing called =E2=80=9Cinvestment securities,=E2=80=9D which *excl=
udes* Treasury securities. Section 3(a)(1)(C) says that a company is an inv=
estment company if more than 40% of its assets are investment securities; S=
PACs are not investment companies under that test. But section 3(a)(1)(A) s=
ays that a company is an investment company if it =E2=80=9Cis or holds itse=
lf out as being engaged primarily, or proposes to engage primarily, in the =
business of investing, reinvesting, or trading in securities=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0securities, not =E2=80=9Cinvestment securities.=E2=80=9D So if =
you launch a Treasury-bond fund whose only business is buying and trading T=
reasuries, that=E2=80=99s an investment company, even though you never buy =
=E2=80=9Cinvestment securities.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;"><em>[5] As Ackman points out in his <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/24831872.264243/aHR0cHM6Ly9wc3RvbnRpbmUuY29tL3dw=
LWNvbnRlbnQvdXBsb2Fkcy8yMDIxLzA4LzguMTkuMjAyMS1QU1RILUxldHRlci10by1TaGFyZWh=
vbGRlcnMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4f6e42d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">letter to PSTH shareholders</a>, one=
 person at the SEC who never noticed this was Robert Jackson. From the lett=
er: =E2=80=9CNotably, one of the professors who is leading the suit, Robert=
 Jackson, served as an SEC Commissioner between January 2018 and February 2=
020. During his more than two-year term as Commissioner, the SEC reviewed a=
nd declared effective more than 100 SPAC IPO registration statements, and o=
versaw dozens of de-SPAC merger transactions. If Mr. Jackson is so sure tha=
t SPACs are in fact illegal investment companies, why didn=E2=80=99t he tak=
e steps to shut them down while he was an SEC Commissioner?=E2=80=9D</em></=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[6] He says =E2=80=9Cwarrants=E2=80=9D w=
here I might prefer to say =E2=80=9Crights.=E2=80=9D The point is, you get =
an option that entitles you to put in money and get back a share of stock i=
n the new company.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[7] Think of it=
 this way: A typical SPAC sells shares for $10, and shareholders get (1) $1=
0 in a pot plus (2) the option to invest that $10 in a deal. That option to=
 invest, for a good SPAC sponsor in good times for SPACs, is worth more tha=
n $0, and during the early-2021=C2=A0SPAC boom many SPACs would quickly tra=
de up to like $12 a share after going public. But the SPAC sponsor wouldn=
=E2=80=99t sell the shares for $12, or whatever the market would bear; the =
sponsor would sell the shares for $10, the amount of cash that it would kee=
p in trust to hand back to shareholders if no deal happened. A SPARC is the=
 same as a SPAC except that instead of $10 in trust it keeps $0 in trust. I=
t=E2=80=99s a SPAC minus $10. As with a SPAC, the option to invest is worth=
 something; $12 minus $10 is $2. But as with a SPAC, you=E2=80=99re not goi=
ng to charge for that option; you=E2=80=99re only going to charge investors=
 the amount of money they=E2=80=99re guaranteed to get back =E2=80=94 here,=
 $0.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[8] Or, if all goes well, you=
 call him in a few months and say =E2=80=9Chey, you=E2=80=99ve got a SPARC.=
=E2=80=9D Same basic principle.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[9=
] Again, though, the other possibility is that my readers are smart but ver=
y ethical; they=C2=A0love thinking of clever hypotheticals but would never =
ever do this.=C2=A0</em></p>
